<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Point_direction_model_arm  Entity: Point_direction  
   <express_ref linkend="point_direction_model:arm:Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction">
        A <b>Point_direction</b> is a type of
        <express_ref linkend="elemental_geometric_shape:arm:Elemental_geometric_shape_arm.Detailed_geometric_model_element"/>
        that represents a location in space of a single axis.
	<example>
		A <b>Point_direction</b> may be used to describe the position and the orientation of a machining tool.
	</example>
</ext_description>

<ext_description linkend="Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction.origin">
	specifies the position of the <b>Point_direction</b> in space.
</ext_description>

<ext_description linkend="Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction.axis">
	specifies the direction of the <b>Point_direction</b> in space.
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Point_direction_model_arm  Entity: Point_direction_model  
   <express_ref linkend="point_direction_model:arm:Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction_model"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction_model">
        A <b>Point_direction_model</b> is a type of
        <express_ref linkend="elemental_geometric_shape:arm:Elemental_geometric_shape_arm.Geometric_model"/>
        that is a model in three-dimensional space consisting only of ordered sequences of points or of points with associated directions.
	<example>
	  For scanned data along planar intersections of a part, or for a model of an item, 
	  several point direction sequences can be used to specify the measured points 
	  together with the measured normal direction on the surface of the object 
	  in their sequence along the planar intersection.
	  Another example is the specification of a tool path where the sequence specifies the tool path as a polygon and the direction specifies the direction of the tool, e.g., a miller, in each point of the path.
	</example>

</ext_description>
<ext_description linkend="Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction_model.items">
	specifies the 
	<express_ref linkend="point_direction_model:arm:Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction_sequence"/> 
	that are the elements of a <b>Point_direction_model</b>.
</ext_description>

<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Point_direction_model_arm  Entity: Point_direction_sequence  
   <express_ref linkend="point_direction_model:arm:Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction_sequence"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
<ext_description linkend="Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction_sequence">
        A <b>Point_direction_sequence</b> is a type of
        <express_ref linkend="elemental_geometric_shape:arm:Elemental_geometric_shape_arm.Detailed_geometric_model_element"/>
        that represents an ordered list of points together with their associated directions.
	<example>
		A <b>Point_direction_sequence</b> may be used to represent the consecutive locations of a cutting tool during a machining operation.
	</example>
</ext_description>

<ext_description linkend="Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction_sequence.items">
  specifies the 
  <express_ref linkend="point_direction_model:arm:Point_direction_model_arm.Point_direction"/> 
  objects or the 
  <express_ref linkend="basic_geometry:arm:Basic_geometry_arm.Point_on_surface"/> 
  objects that define the consecutive points and the appropriate axis directions. 
  In the case of a 
  <express_ref linkend="basic_geometry:arm:Basic_geometry_arm.Point_on_surface"/>,
  the direction is the cross product of the principal tangent vectors u and v of the surface in this point.
  There shall be at least one object that defines the element for a <b>Point_direction_sequence</b>.
</ext_description>

